PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Moody's Investors Service placed Ashland Inc.'s ASH junk-level ratings under review for a possible downgrade, citing the chemical company's planned acquisition of International Specialty Products Inc. Ashland said Tuesday it would pay $3.2 billion in cash to buy the specialty-chemicals supplier, a move that would expand its personal care, pharmaceutical and energy businesses. Ashland currently has a Moody's corporate family rating of Ba1, one notch below investment-grade. Moody's said its review will focus on the outlook for the combined companies, any potential restructuring actions, any liabilities assumed and the pace at which the company expects to repay the acquisition debt.

Headlines.Headline: EU Crt Says REACH Rules On Monomers, Polymers Valid

PARAGRAPH.#text: (Adds detail) LUXEMBOURG (Dow Jones)--Europe's highest court has ruled that a provision in the European Union's chemical regulation REACH, requiring monomers that have been reacted to form polymers to be registered, is valid. The court found that the regulation's coverage of monomers, chemical building blocks that create polymers when they are reacted and linked together, should be considered to include the reacted monomers that have bound together to make a polymer. The court was hearing a judicial reference from the U.K.'s High Court, which is considering challenges from several companies over the regulation's provisions on monomers and polymers.

PARAGRAPH.#text: By Christopher Hinton In the rock pools along the North Atlantic lives a worm that may hold a clue for aerospace engineers looking for stronger, lighter materials to build aircraft that can fly greater distances and burn less fuel. The ragworm, also called a clamworm or Nereis virens by the scientists who study it, has a unique set of pincers that it uses to tear apart food and fight off predators. Fascinating to researchers is that the pincers have a high concentration of zinc, which is usually deadly to organisms in large amounts.
